As a result, for many, there has never been a more important time for people to check whether they qualify for free prescriptions. Typically, 15 groups of Britons qualify for help towards medical costs including NHS prescriptions and dental treatment.  The Department for Health and Social Care (DHSC) recently confirmed NHS prescription charges won’t increase this year. Although they will remain at £9.35 per item, some people could still struggle to meet these costs due to the cost of living crisis. However, people on certain Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) benefits should be exempt from paying. At the same time, Britons who suffer from certain medical conditions should also qualify for free prescriptions. READ MORE: 'No regrets!' Mum shares the 'easy way' she makes extra £830 a month Universal Credit claimants could be eligible if they earn less than a certain amount. They may also qualify if they earn more, but have dependent children. People should qualify if they: DON'T MISS:Is it cheaper to heat one room with an electric heater?Housing Benefit rule stopping Britons from receiving full entitlementPension tax warning: Savers hit with 55% charge on their pension pots  In addition, the other DWP benefits that qualify for free prescriptions and dental care are: Anyone who doesn’t qualify for Government help but is struggling financially should consider investing in a Pre Payment Certificate (PPC). This allows people to purchase as many NHS prescriptions as they need for a one off cost. Depending on how many prescriptions someone needs throughout the year, it could save them a fortune. It works out at £30.25 for three months or £108.10 for a year and can be purchased from the NHS website. What is happening where you live? Find out by adding your postcode or visit InYourArea Meanwhile, people with certain medical conditions should qualify for a Medical Exemption Certificate if they have: